00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:43.230
What doesn't work?

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:47.470
Dollar-cost averaging is
familiar to most of you.

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:52.280
Google has a 401k plan,
I assume, being a very

00:03:52.280 --> 00:03:54.070
forward-thinking company.

00:03:54.070 --> 00:03:57.630
And so if you participate in
every paycheck, money comes

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:01.670
out and you direct its
investment in options that the

00:04:01.670 --> 00:04:04.220
401k provider offers.

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:06.280
Primarily mutual funds?

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:07.620
You can't buy individual
stocks?

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:08.330
AUDIENCE: Yes, you can.

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:09.500
TOM JACOBS: You can.

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:11.830
AUDIENCE: It's [? Vanguard. ?]

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:13.700
TOM JACOBS: Good.

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:14.430
Excellent.

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:18.089
Excellent, so you can
get into trouble.

00:04:18.089 --> 00:04:20.890
No, but I mean, that's a very
good option, particularly for

00:04:20.890 --> 00:04:24.540
people who spend a lot of
time working on this.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:27.790
The problem with dollar-cost
averaging is that what happens

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:31.250
is that people stop making their
payroll deductions or

00:04:31.250 --> 00:04:34.770
they move them to cash, and they
lose the benefits of the

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:38.460
automatic averaging
that you get.

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:41.990
The problem with investing for
many people, even in indexes,

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:45.740
is that you inadvertently market
time unless you're

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:50.690
doing it mechanically every
single pay period, averaging

00:04:50.690 --> 00:04:54.790
out your purchase
price, right?

00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:57.710
The problem is that it
requires discipline.

00:04:57.710 --> 00:04:59.780
There was a great study that
Morningstar did where they

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:03.270
looked at the returns of CGM
focus funds Ken Heebner, who

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:05.180
Peter Lynch called one
of the greatest

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:06.620
investors of all time.

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:09.410
Heebner's had incredible
results, but has high

00:05:09.410 --> 00:05:11.050
volatility, right?

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:13.210
Up and down high beta
to the averages.

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:15.560
Morningstar found that while
Heebner did extraordinarily

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.440
well, his investors did not.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:21.300
They would sell after a bad year
and then they would buy

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:24.710
after a good year, selling
low and buying high.

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:28.080
This actually is what
most people do.

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:29.780
The other thing that dollar-cost
averaging requires

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:31.480
is a steady income cycle.

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:34.510
And I had the pleasure of
speaking the other night to a

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:38.050
group of people, a number of
whom had been laid off by HP,

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:40.120
and they were actually--

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:41.520
I shouldn't say this--
they were actually

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:42.720
very happy to be gone.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:45.085
But they had--

00:05:45.085 --> 00:05:46.360
they were--

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:47.760
and they had a lot of money.

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.290
They got big lump sums
of payouts and so on.

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:52.640
And they said, well, Tom I can't
dollar-cost average.

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:53.790
What do I do?

00:05:53.790 --> 00:05:57.020
So it just doesn't
fit most people.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:06:00.040
And psychologically, we know
from behavioral finance, this

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:03.000
is very difficult for people.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.160
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: This is one
of my favorite charts.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.630
