of Individual

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:12.050
Investors, which is most of
us in the room here today.

00:06:12.050 --> 00:06:15.030
This shows the three time
periods of the highest cash

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:17.590
position and the lowest cash
position and then today.

00:06:17.590 --> 00:06:20.310
And we'll get more into the
market view at the end of the

00:06:20.310 --> 00:06:21.040
presentation.

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:24.290
But I wanted to highlight
the extremes that occur.

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:30.260
The highest cash position ever
was in March of 2009 at 45%.

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:32.570
If you remember, that's the
exact low of the market.

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:34.980
So, at this point in time,
everybody was slashing their

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:37.310
wrists and running under hot
water when they should have

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:40.060
been buying stock.

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:43.670
And they had 14% bonds and
just 41% in equities.

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:47.060
And now we've been in a massive
44 month move off the

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:49.610
bottom where equities have
well more than doubled.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:51.360
And if you've picked individual
stocks, in many

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:54.680
cases they're up
1,000% or more.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:58.010
The lowest cash position of all
time was March of 1998.

00:06:58.010 --> 00:07:01.000
And for those you old enough to
remember the internet boom

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.700
that ultimately crashed, that
was right around the time when

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:04.410
it was getting into--

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:07.430
TOM JACOBS: Oh, I
remember that.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:08.430
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: Yeah, that
was pretty painful.

00:07:08.430 --> 00:07:11.910
So everyone was fully invested
here at this time frame.

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:15.480
74% was held in stocks and
just 15% in bonds.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:18.550
Today, we are at 18.8% cash.

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:20.250
And there's a notion that
there's a lot of cash on the

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:22.320
sidelines in the marketplace,
and that's going to drive the

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:23.780
stock market higher.

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:25.940
I would argue that that's
not going to occur.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:27.570
You have to remember that
this was during a

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:30.160
once-in-a-generation bubble
period that occurs about once

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:31.810
every 25 years.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:34.320
It takes a long time to work off
of that until someone is

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:37.540
stupid enough to create
the next big bubble.

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:41.170
And we're at 18.8 and this was
11, so if you cut it in half,

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:44.290
maybe there's 4% more that
could go into equities.

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:46.970
But we also see a lot
more into bonds.

00:07:46.970 --> 00:07:49.670
15% bonds here and there's
21% bonds here.

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:50.890
Why is that?

00:07:50.890 --> 00:07:53.590
It's because demographics
have changed.

00:07:53.590 --> 00:07:55.880
The investors in 1998 have
gotten a lot older.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:57.660
It's 14 years later.

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:00.420
My mother, for instance,
was a baby boomer.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:03.290
Her highest earning years
were from 1980 to 1999.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:05.720
She worked for Bristol-Myers
Squibb.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:09.220
She had a 401k plan, no college
education, she had

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:13.710
stock options, cash bonuses,
health care.

00:08:13.710 --> 00:08:15.840
Most of that stuff has
gone away now.

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:21.080
She was fortunate enough to
retire in 1999, and kind of

00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:22.200
rode off into the sunset.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:24.960
But for the most part, that's
not really happening today for

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:25.660
a lot of people.

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:28.950
So I would argue that this
cash position is probably

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:30.930
about as low as it's going to
get, maybe just a couple

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:32.120
percent lower.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:36.130
And that's why you need to be
defensive in your portfolio.

00:08:36.130 --> 00:08:38.530
But these individual investors
are usually horrible at

00:08:38.530 --> 00:08:42.150
allocating capital, and that's
really been the case over the

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:43.850
last 30 or 40 years.

00:08:43.850 --> 00:08:46.100
TOM JACOBS: And even the
big asset allocators--

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:51.170
brokers who have their clients
in programs where they'll have

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:54.460
more options, precious metals
and so on, 2008 killed it.

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.420
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: And we'll
get into that as well.

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:58.420
Active investment managers
who are quote unquote

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:00.430
"professionals" are just
as bad as individuals.

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:01.447
And I'll show you an
even worse chart

00:09:01.447 --> 00:09:02.347
when we get to that.

00:09:02.347 --> 00:09:03.720
TOM JACOBS: Right.

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:05.890
What investors want is safety.

00:09:05.890 --> 00:09:08.020
They want to buy and forget,
and they want inflation

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:08.960
protection.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:13.840
What they get is volatility,
which scares them into selling

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:15.550
low and buying high.

00:09:15.550 --> 00:09:19.650
They buy, forget, and then they
lose, and inflation is

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:21.500
beyond their control.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:24.280
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: Today's
winners are tomorrow's losers.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:27.800
So growth loses over time.

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:29.400
And the stocks from
one generation--

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:31.750
their leaders are generally not
the leaders of the next.

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:35.190
So imagine that we are here in
1979 and I told you that we

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:37.550
were talking about Eastman
Kodak, and Polaroid, and

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:40.440
companies like that that were
Nifty Fifty stocks.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:42.260
And I said, in 30 years they're
either going to be

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:43.990
bankrupt or bailed out
by the government,

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:45.280
or cut their dividends.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:47.310
That would sound like blasphemy,
but that's exactly

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:48.800
what happened.

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:50.720
Roll forward to the
internet boom.

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:55.940
You've got Microsoft, Intel,
Cisco, Dell, Hewlett-Packard,

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:58.050
those were kind of the big
horsemen of the internet and

00:09:58.050 --> 00:09:59.420
the PC cycle.

00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:01.740
That's pretty much been dead
money for the last 14 years.

00:10:01.740 --> 00:10:04.700
So if you're a wealth adviser,
and you've got your clients in

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:07.260
those stocks, you probably
got fired.

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:10.730
The bull leaders lose 80% in
the next cycle, that's

00:10:10.730 --> 00:10:12.080
research by William O'Neil.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.450
He's the publisher of
"Investor's Business Daily,"

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:17.220
and has been investing in stocks
for about 50 years.

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:20.280
And so you can't just buy a
stock and forget about it.

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:24.120
Times change, the environment
changes, the economy changes,

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:26.710
technology changes, and so
buying for the long term is

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:29.810
actually very dangerous, unless
you're just buying an

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:32.620
index fund and holding that
over a time period.

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:35.190
So what we're going to tell you
to do, or show you how to

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:38.292
do, is avoid the losers before
they become a big torpedo in

00:10:38.292 --> 00:10:39.640
your portfolio.

