Well, we could argue
about that.

00:11:11.560 --> 00:11:11.920
TOM JACOBS: Right, we
could argue about

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:14.610
that, or until today.

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:16.980
Now what I'd like to point out
here is that inflation

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:19.730
protection is entirely
an accident of birth.

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:22.270
Typically we have high inflation
in war time,

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:25.120
followed by high deflation
as the stimulus

00:11:25.120 --> 00:11:26.120
is taken out after.

00:11:26.120 --> 00:11:27.530
And this is--

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:30.160
World War I was an
example of this.

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:34.170
World War II, where we ended up
with 90% marginal highest

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:37.580
tax rate because we needed to
fund the war and then printed

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:38.700
money to do it.

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:41.910
Now, what we got from the
Bush administration--

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:44.840
and this is not political,
it's just a fact--

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:46.270
was guns and butter.

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:51.360
And as you all remember from
Econ 101, if you have both,

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:52.900
eventually you'll
have inflation.

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:56.670
Under Lyndon Johnson, we had
guns and butter, and

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:58.330
eventually that led
to inflation.

00:11:58.330 --> 00:12:02.260
I mean, the idea was, give
people benefits at the same

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:06.240
time that you fund the war,
it's fiscal policy that

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:07.810
usually leads to inflation.

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:11.780
So for example, in the 1970s--

00:12:11.780 --> 00:12:15.800
when you add in inflation and so
on-- the average annual S&amp;P

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:21.535
500 return, the real return--

00:12:21.535 --> 00:12:22.800
what do I mean there?

00:12:25.470 --> 00:12:29.030
All right, let's just say it was
negative every year for 10

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:29.980
years, all right?

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:33.160
And so, if you just happened to
be in that high inflation

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:37.330
period, and that really got bad
in '81 and '82, it was an

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:39.060
absolutely lost decade.

00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:44.500
For example, from 1968 to
1982, the Dow was flat.

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:45.140
Absolutely flat.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:46.850
So I said, OK, it
wasn't so bad.

00:12:46.850 --> 00:12:48.260
Maybe I got some dividends.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:49.840
But the purchasing power--

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:52.290
we argue over this--
dropped 50%.

00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:53.900
John says he's seen higher.

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:56.310
So most people don't think
about inflation.

00:12:56.310 --> 00:12:58.330
They don't think about real
returns, they think about

00:12:58.330 --> 00:13:01.290
nominal returns.

00:13:01.290 --> 00:13:04.480
A little known fact is that if
you had been able to keep your

00:13:04.480 --> 00:13:07.860
money after the crash of '29--
and of course the problem was

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:09.470
most people couldn't, right--

00:13:09.470 --> 00:13:11.990
you lose your job, you have
to spend your savings.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:16.730
But actually, the purchasing
power of the money was back in

00:13:16.730 --> 00:13:18.590
seven years, by 1936.

00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:20.940
And what we hear all the time is
it the averages didn't come

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:24.710
back until the early '40s for
the S&amp;P, and the early '50s

00:13:24.710 --> 00:13:26.270
for the Dow.

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:28.210
But that's nominal.

00:13:28.210 --> 00:13:34.220
In real returns, you had the
same purchasing power by 1936.

00:13:34.220 --> 00:13:38.280
And also in the 2000s, you can
see a combination of inflation

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:41.130
and stock market return,
another lost decade.

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.030
With inflation, it's just
when you're born.

00:13:44.030 --> 00:13:49.190
Stocks do not protect against
inflation, maybe if you had 40

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:51.400
years, 30 years.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.900
But most of us have a 20 to
25 year investing life.

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:58.920
Kids, the mortgage,
the underwater--

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.210
OK.

