the company goes public--

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:17.200
so on their initial public
offering, and they're flush

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:19.670
with cash, and then they
make acquisitions.

00:29:19.670 --> 00:29:22.330
It actually still obscures the
financial statements, because

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:24.620
the way the purchase accounting
works is from the

00:29:24.620 --> 00:29:28.160
day they make the acquisition
forward, it's two combined

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:30.650
companies, not ever
looking back.

00:29:30.650 --> 00:29:34.390
So if I have $100 in revenue and
you have $10 in revenue, I

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:36.250
can make it look like
10% growth, even

00:29:36.250 --> 00:29:37.870
though nothing changed.

00:29:37.870 --> 00:29:39.920
Under poolings of interest,
which is what Cisco, when they

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:41.880
were really growing, was doing,
it actually made the

00:29:41.880 --> 00:29:44.410
