job, basically

00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:13.280
given all this money.

00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:15.980
Make this the best engineering
school in the country.

00:34:15.980 --> 00:34:17.730
They got a huge amount
of money.

00:34:17.730 --> 00:34:22.489
And as I was telling Alex at
lunch, I went to see him, we

00:34:22.489 --> 00:34:23.909
had a friend's reunion
in August.

00:34:23.909 --> 00:34:26.570
And he told me, Tom, I just want
to explain why you need

00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:28.030
an Android phone.

00:34:28.030 --> 00:34:28.659
OK?

00:34:28.659 --> 00:34:31.380
I just want to explain to you
why Google is great and Apple

00:34:31.380 --> 00:34:34.270
is now as evil as Microsoft.

00:34:34.270 --> 00:34:37.870
And he showed me the amount of
data he is processing all

00:34:37.870 --> 00:34:39.150
around the world all day long.

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:44.460
He's testing solar panels,
it's all amazing.

00:34:44.460 --> 00:34:46.860
Free Google software.

00:34:46.860 --> 00:34:50.429
He is using something
probably some of you

00:34:50.429 --> 00:34:52.770
made, and it's free.

00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:55.780
And he could not do his
job without it.

00:34:55.780 --> 00:34:59.080
So all these companies that
he's testing whether these

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:01.550
solar panels will really
last 20 years or

00:35:01.550 --> 00:35:04.440
not, free Google software.

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:05.230
That's all it took.

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:07.430
I was done.

00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:10.410
I can't value a Facebook.

00:35:10.410 --> 00:35:14.090
I don't know if it will
become like Myspace.

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:16.890
I think the advertising
model is a great one.

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:20.340
I was just never very
good at intangibles.

00:35:20.340 --> 00:35:22.550
Tangibles, they have prices.

00:35:22.550 --> 00:35:23.600
They're quoted every day.

00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:25.340
Commodities.

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:27.456
Rents for commercial
buildings.

00:35:27.456 --> 00:35:28.230
All right.

00:35:28.230 --> 00:35:31.860
I think I've beaten that
horse to death.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:33.240
Low multiple of cash flow.

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:36.650
Now, Tweedy, Browne used P/E,
and that's because for decades

00:35:36.650 --> 00:35:39.060
and decades and decades, the
price to earnings ratio was

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:39.940
all you had.

00:35:39.940 --> 00:35:43.310
In fact, it was only in the late
1960s that companies were

00:35:43.310 --> 00:35:46.680
required to report the cash
flow statement at all.

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:49.610
Value investors love the balance
sheet and the cash

00:35:49.610 --> 00:35:50.340
flow statement.

00:35:50.340 --> 00:35:52.270
And part of the reason, as John
has demonstrated, the

00:35:52.270 --> 00:35:56.320
income statement is not the only
one, but a large place

00:35:56.320 --> 00:35:57.460
where the shenanigans--

00:35:57.460 --> 00:35:59.210
or chicanery, as we say--

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:00.230
take place.

00:36:00.230 --> 00:36:04.310
So I'm looking for low
enterprise value or market cap

00:36:04.310 --> 00:36:06.180
to free cash flow.

00:36:06.180 --> 00:36:08.670
How much actual cash is the
company throwing out?

00:36:08.670 --> 00:36:11.100
Now, it can be a trap.

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:14.200
Bridgepoint Education is one
of these not for profit

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:17.100
education companies and selling,
basically, for a

00:36:17.100 --> 00:36:21.270
dollar more than net cash per
share on its balance sheet.

00:36:21.270 --> 00:36:23.550
You'd think it would be
something I would love-- buy a

00:36:23.550 --> 00:36:24.710
cheap asset.

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:25.970
But it's intangible.

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:26.870
It's not buildings.

00:36:26.870 --> 00:36:30.080
It's whatever brand they have
that can get students to get

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:34.640
government loans, to pay for
courses, and maybe not get

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:38.850
jobs because the industry is
very much in its infancy.

00:36:38.850 --> 00:36:40.960
So you would think
someone like me

00:36:40.960 --> 00:36:43.040
would buy it down here--

00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:45.370
price, of course, is not a
reflection of valuation, but

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:47.840
in this case, it's very
close to net cash.

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:50.500
I'm buying an asset for
a very low price.

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:52.490
I have cash protection.

00:36:52.490 --> 00:36:56.530
But I really don't know what th
asset is worth, so I can't

00:36:56.530 --> 00:37:00.680
say am I getting it for 50
cents on the dollar?

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:04.010
That's called a value trap,
where value investors will get

00:37:04.010 --> 00:37:07.810
all excited about it and
nothing happens.

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:10.790
Why do we care about low
price to assets and low

00:37:10.790 --> 00:37:12.610
price to cash flow?

00:37:12.610 --> 00:37:16.700
If it gets low enough, and the
business is at least steady

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:20.570
state, someone will buy you.

00:37:20.570 --> 00:37:21.820
Guaranteed.

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:26.840
Or someone will come in and
say, you're running your

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:29.630
business terribly, it's
reflected in your valuation.

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:31.310
I'll buy up a lot
of your stock.

00:37:31.310 --> 00:37:35.770
Carl Icahn, Bill Ackman, and
some other names that are not

00:37:35.770 --> 00:37:37.160
household names.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:39.770
They'll buy up a lot of stock
and agitate for you to spin

00:37:39.770 --> 00:37:42.680
off a business.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:45.880
Berkshire Hathaway gets what's
called a conglomerate discount

00:37:45.880 --> 00:37:48.490
because we know he will never
sell off businesses.

00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:53.120
If he did spin off businesses
and you owned Berkshire today,

00:37:53.120 --> 00:37:56.660
your stocks all together,
after he spun off the

00:37:56.660 --> 00:37:59.760
businesses in the public
markets, would be worth more.

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:03.200
So we say it's a conglomerate
discount when you don't think

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:05.360
they're going to spin
off businesses.

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:07.370
You're never going
to realize that.

00:38:07.370 --> 00:38:08.610
So [? activist ?]

00:38:08.610 --> 00:38:12.010
shareholders will come in and
try to create value through

00:38:12.010 --> 00:38:16.420
catalysts to realize value,
such as spinoffs and

00:38:16.420 --> 00:38:17.630
mergers and so on.

00:38:17.630 --> 00:38:19.870
By the way, everybody thinks
that their merger is going to

00:38:19.870 --> 00:38:21.120
be like Lake Wobegon.

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:25.320
85% of them don't add
shareholder value.

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:28.880
15% do, according to a study
at Harvard, but everybody

00:38:28.880 --> 00:38:32.080
thinks their acquisition
will be above average.

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:33.900
Share repurchases.

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:38.090
Tweedy, Browne looks at insider
buying in their five

00:38:38.090 --> 00:38:40.950
points of what works
in investing.

00:38:40.950 --> 00:38:43.990
I would say that most insiders
of companies are no better

00:38:43.990 --> 00:38:48.000
investors than the average
investor-- a lot of them.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.270
Now, they do know stuff.

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:52.560
They do know that things are
coming down the pike, but, of

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:56.960
course, they're prevented for
acting on a lot of information

00:38:56.960 --> 00:38:59.590
in certain legal
circumstances.

00:38:59.590 --> 00:39:03.170
So I prefer to see share
[INAUDIBLE] purchases that are

00:39:03.170 --> 00:39:05.650
bought when the valuation
is cheap.

00:39:05.650 --> 00:39:07.980
When I would buy the stock
because it's selling for a

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:11.780
discount to assets, that's when
I want the company buying

00:39:11.780 --> 00:39:12.710
back stock.

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:16.230
I want them buying back stock
when that investment--

00:39:16.230 --> 00:39:19.440
when the stock value is so much
below its real worth due

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:25.650
emotion, due to the Mr. market
we saw, fear that that's a

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:27.080
better investment.

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:29.100
Buying back to the stock
at a discount.

00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:33.880
It's like me or you buying the
stock at a discount than

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:37.490
wasting it on acquisitions
that destroy value.

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:39.210
I've never owned Berkshire
Hathaway.

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:42.620
I would today, because they now
have an absolute policy.

00:39:42.620 --> 00:39:48.090
They buy back stock whenever
it's 110% of book value,

00:39:48.090 --> 00:39:50.760
shareholder equity, or less.

00:39:50.760 --> 00:39:51.890
Automatic.

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:54.410
Down to where their cash
is $20 billion.

00:39:54.410 --> 00:39:56.610
They have a lot more
than $20 billion.

00:39:56.610 --> 00:39:59.600
So that that's like a support
under the stock.

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:02.830
Every time it gets to a certain
low value, they whoosh

00:40:02.830 --> 00:40:04.110
in, they buy it.

00:40:04.110 --> 00:40:07.210
It's protection.

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:09.830
The fourth point is a large
decline in stock price due to

00:40:09.830 --> 00:40:10.900
emotional reaction.

00:40:10.900 --> 00:40:13.830
That's because stock prices tend
to revert to the mean,

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:17.280
which is why paying up for a
hypergrowth stock almost

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:20.490
always ends up in paying.

00:40:20.490 --> 00:40:22.870
What goes up must come down.

00:40:22.870 --> 00:40:25.570
What goes down comes back up.

00:40:25.570 --> 00:40:29.996
Now, obviously, not in
the case of Google.

00:40:29.996 --> 00:40:31.214
All right.

00:40:31.214 --> 00:40:32.840
AUDIENCE: But I'm guessing
in the case of Apple, so.

00:40:32.840 --> 00:40:33.130
TOM JACOBS: Yeah.

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:33.710
But in the case of
Apple, right?

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:36.410
Now, I apologize in advance
for choosing the

00:40:36.410 --> 00:40:39.710
Macondo in the Gulf.

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:46.416
It's obviously a horrible
tragedy for the people on it,

00:40:46.416 --> 00:40:49.200
for people who depended
on the Gulf, for the

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:50.640
environment of the Gulf.

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:54.440
However, I think that by
choosing something like this,

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:57.750
something so extreme, it's
useful to make a point.

00:40:57.750 --> 00:41:02.990
So I apologize in advance for
saying you could make money in

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:04.140
this kind of environment.

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:07.920
But I think that it shows
you that in far lesser

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:10.090
circumstances, you
can, as well.

00:41:10.090 --> 00:41:15.140
So this is an emotional event
that will cause assets to sell

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:18.480
at less than their real
value because

00:41:18.480 --> 00:41:20.110
everybody throws it out.

00:41:20.110 --> 00:41:22.370
They're scared to
death, right?

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:27.080
So that blue arrow is
Ensco, a driller--

00:41:27.080 --> 00:41:28.475
an oil rig owner and driller.

00:41:28.475 --> 00:41:30.600
They rent themselves out,
these big, huge

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:34.760
semi-submersible and drill
3,000, 12,000, 10,000 feet

00:41:34.760 --> 00:41:35.940
below the ocean for oil.

00:41:35.940 --> 00:41:37.220
And which--

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:37.580
oh, gosh.

00:41:37.580 --> 00:41:39.820
I'm sort of in your way.

00:41:39.820 --> 00:41:44.480
And which produce
where the oil's

00:41:44.480 --> 00:41:46.890
coming from today, really.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:51.160
So Macondo happens.

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:55.090
Transocean's Deep Horizon
rig blows up.

00:41:55.090 --> 00:41:57.830
All the drillers go down,
every single one.

00:41:57.830 --> 00:42:00.520
BP crashes, Transocean
crashes--

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:02.510
all the drillers you
can imagine.

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:05.760
Which, of course, at the
particular moment, being in

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.120
front of you, I can't
summon up.

00:42:07.120 --> 00:42:08.340
But I know what I did.

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:11.900
That weekend, I went home and
I looked at all the drillers

00:42:11.900 --> 00:42:15.780
and I said, this is a time to
look for a company that has

00:42:15.780 --> 00:42:19.910
little to no exposure to the
Gulf, has an excellent safety

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:24.190
record, but yet has been
hit like all of them--

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:26.980
has a great balance sheet.

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:29.860
And Ensco was the
one I picked.

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:31.960
Eventually, you had reversion
to the mean.

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:35.400
When the fear was over, I
happened to sell not at the

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:37.440
top-- you never buy at the
bottom or sell at the top--

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:40.660
but we made some good money for
special ops members at the

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:42.620
Motley Fool.

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:45.800
I think that others
did better.

00:42:45.800 --> 00:42:48.610
If you bought BP, it may
have done better.

00:42:48.610 --> 00:42:51.200
If you bought Transocean, you
definitely did better.

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:52.570
But why didn't I buy it?

00:42:52.570 --> 00:42:59.530
Because I couldn't value the
asset because the liability

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:00.580
was unknown.

00:43:00.580 --> 00:43:02.210
We didn't know how much
they were going to end

00:43:02.210 --> 00:43:03.750
up having to pay.

00:43:03.750 --> 00:43:05.020
It was a big unknown.

00:43:05.020 --> 00:43:06.690
With Ensco, I can see
the contracts.

00:43:06.690 --> 00:43:08.000
They have them on their
site-- where all the

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:09.330
rigs are and so on.

00:43:09.330 --> 00:43:10.070
All right.

00:43:10.070 --> 00:43:13.620
Small market cap is
a key element.

00:43:13.620 --> 00:43:16.680
Small companies, there's less
information about them.

00:43:16.680 --> 00:43:20.900
So if you do the work,
you can uncover gems.

00:43:20.900 --> 00:43:23.220
However, they tend to be more
volatile because they have

00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:24.360
less volume.

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:28.660
So here's one of my favorites,
because it was a success.

00:43:28.660 --> 00:43:32.080
We all had failures, but this
one has worked out well.

00:43:32.080 --> 00:43:34.670
But just a little bit
of volume there--

00:43:34.670 --> 00:43:35.890
that's what I guess [? they ?]

00:43:35.890 --> 00:43:37.560
[? call ?] gapping up.

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:40.870
It just zoomed up when the
Mexican Tax Authorities gave

00:43:40.870 --> 00:43:45.070
them a favorable ruling on
treatment of silver taxation,

00:43:45.070 --> 00:43:47.670
giving them another $20
to $40 million a year.

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:51.050
When you're a $200 million
market cap company, $20 to $40

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:53.045
million is a lot of dough.

00:43:53.045 --> 00:43:56.800
However, it's been
very volatile--

00:43:56.800 --> 00:44:00.030
overreacted, now, coming
back down.

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:03.050
So what happens, though, is that
the more money you have,

00:44:03.050 --> 00:44:05.140
the fewer small caps
you can buy.

00:44:05.140 --> 00:44:05.400
Buffett--

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:07.670
it was $43 billion in cash.

00:44:07.670 --> 00:44:10.970
Do you think the $240 million
Primero Mining matters to him?

00:44:10.970 --> 00:44:12.390
It doesn't even--

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:13.730
cliche alert--

00:44:13.730 --> 00:44:15.690
move the needle.

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:18.080
So, as all these guys--

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:21.120
the great Yale University
endowment manager, David

00:44:21.120 --> 00:44:24.660
Swensen, and many say, size
is the enemy of returns.

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:28.190
It decreases the universe
of stocks you can buy.

00:44:28.190 --> 00:44:31.460
If small caps provide the best
returns over time, provided

00:44:31.460 --> 00:44:33.740
you apply all of the strategies
I'm pointing out

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:37.240
from Tweedy, Browne, you
all end up like rats

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:38.820
in a large cap cage.

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:40.410
All these big companies--

00:44:40.410 --> 00:44:41.940
they're looking at
the same ones.

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:46.570
They're trying to find if
your $1, undervalued,

00:44:46.570 --> 00:44:49.060
or Microsoft, $2--

00:44:49.060 --> 00:44:50.590
it's all the same companies.

00:44:50.590 --> 00:44:54.420
And it's really hard to
make money that way.

00:44:54.420 --> 00:44:55.160
So what do you do?

00:44:55.160 --> 00:44:56.300
The more money you have--

00:44:56.300 --> 00:45:00.110
which would be a nice problem
for a lot of us, to have a

00:45:00.110 --> 00:45:03.100
billion or something--

00:45:03.100 --> 00:45:04.480
you look for activists,
you look for

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:06.240
catalysts, and large caps.

00:45:06.240 --> 00:45:09.490
These will be people like Ackman
at JC Penney, who has

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:12.000
control of General Growth
Properties, which he was

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:17.260
scooping up at $0.50
which is $19.

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:19.720
Carl Icahn is now doing
this in natural gas

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:21.010
at Chesapeake Energy.

00:45:21.010 --> 00:45:24.260
I'm a big natural
gas contrarian.

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:26.030
And, of course, in this, to
succeed, you have to be

00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:26.980
contrarian.

00:45:26.980 --> 00:45:29.170
Now, whether that will play
out, I don't know.

00:45:29.170 --> 00:45:32.940
And then other catalysts
that unlock value.

