TOM JACOBS: So this was a
question talking about large

01:06:42.200 --> 01:06:44.130
cap dividend payers.

01:06:44.130 --> 01:06:45.990
Is there a threshold
for the yield?

01:06:45.990 --> 01:06:47.170
Is that what you're saying?

01:06:47.170 --> 01:06:50.560
I would like to just address
that one of the issues,

01:06:50.560 --> 01:06:54.170
unfortunately, with dividend
payers is that

01:06:54.170 --> 01:06:56.200
it's not just yield.

01:06:56.200 --> 01:06:58.800
Unfortunately, you really have
to look at what percentage of

01:06:58.800 --> 01:07:02.530
revenues, free cash flow, and
income is getting paid out.

01:07:02.530 --> 01:07:04.450
Because the last thing
you want is the

01:07:04.450 --> 01:07:06.290
dividend to get cut.

01:07:06.290 --> 01:07:08.530
For example, Shippers.

01:07:08.530 --> 01:07:09.470
They have good times.

01:07:09.470 --> 01:07:11.640
They pay 11% out, 12%.

01:07:11.640 --> 01:07:13.010
That looks really great.

01:07:13.010 --> 01:07:15.770
But Shippers, they pay
everything out as dividends

01:07:15.770 --> 01:07:18.490
when times are good, and then
they cut it when it's down.

01:07:18.490 --> 01:07:20.900
And it happens over and
over and over again.

01:07:20.900 --> 01:07:23.230
So as a rule of thumb, you don't
want a company that's

01:07:23.230 --> 01:07:27.610
paying out more than 50% of free
cash flow or net income.

01:07:27.610 --> 01:07:29.640
So you do have to
actually look.

01:07:29.640 --> 01:07:32.950
The other thing is, if they're
growing, it's more likely that

01:07:32.950 --> 01:07:35.330
they will be able to increase
the dividend.

01:07:35.330 --> 01:07:35.750
Fair enough?

01:07:35.750 --> 01:07:36.480
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: Yeah.

01:07:36.480 --> 01:07:39.320
I was just offering that up as a
solution other than shorting

01:07:39.320 --> 01:07:40.790
the market if we're getting
into another

01:07:40.790 --> 01:07:41.940
cyclical bear market.

01:07:41.940 --> 01:07:42.970
TOM JACOBS: That
is [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:42.970 --> 01:07:44.280
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: But if you
look at-- and I believe this

01:07:44.280 --> 01:07:45.860
goes through 2010--

01:07:45.860 --> 01:07:49.650
from 1980ish, when Apple went
public, and compared it to

01:07:49.650 --> 01:07:52.330
Philip Morris, which is pretty
much a sleepy cigarette

01:07:52.330 --> 01:07:56.130
business that had multi-business
units.

01:07:56.130 --> 01:07:57.470
Apple stock is up--

01:07:57.470 --> 01:07:58.840
I'm making up the numbers now
because I don't have it in

01:07:58.840 --> 01:08:02.710
front of me, but it's up like,
say, 7,500% or 10,000%, and

01:08:02.710 --> 01:08:05.210
Philip Morris, with those
dividends and reinvested

01:08:05.210 --> 01:08:07.350
dividends is up 20,000%.

01:08:07.350 --> 01:08:11.080
In other words, the dividend
is a real key component to

01:08:11.080 --> 01:08:13.360
long-term growth in
your portfolio.

01:08:13.360 --> 01:08:15.780
And so you should at least think
about them when you're

01:08:15.780 --> 01:08:17.439
going out there and picking
individual stocks.

01:08:17.439 --> 01:08:20.010
TOM JACOBS: And i think that the
point also is protecting

01:08:20.010 --> 01:08:22.910
yourself if we're going
to have a large drop.

01:08:22.910 --> 01:08:25.460
I don't think it's like,
suddenly we're talking about

01:08:25.460 --> 01:08:30.275
the long side of the portfolio
conforming to the points that

01:08:30.275 --> 01:08:31.529
I made from the study.

01:08:31.529 --> 01:08:37.279
It's something you might
consider facing the kind of

01:08:37.279 --> 01:08:40.609
long-term, possibly negative
annualized returns that the

01:08:40.609 --> 01:08:43.130
market is telling
us we'll have.

01:08:43.130 --> 01:08:48.410
Now, to be fair to your question
in another way, the

01:08:48.410 --> 01:08:52.630
answer easily is dollar-cost
averaging discipline.

01:08:52.630 --> 01:08:54.149
That's really the response.

01:08:54.149 --> 01:08:56.810
Because otherwise,
what do you do?

01:08:56.810 --> 01:08:59.939
But that gets us back to
whether you can do it.

01:08:59.939 --> 01:09:01.390
Some of you can do this.

01:09:01.390 --> 01:09:03.710
I know people that can do that
in their discipline.

01:09:03.710 --> 01:09:06.120
But what I didn't want to do at
the beginning was to have

01:09:06.120 --> 01:09:11.450
any doubt that the academic
studies show most

01:09:11.450 --> 01:09:14.460
people can't do that.

01:09:14.460 --> 01:09:16.010
And that's where the
opportunities come in.

01:09:16.010 --> 01:09:18.930
But if you can do that,
you can do that

01:09:18.930 --> 01:09:21.060
and go home, basically.

01:09:21.060 --> 01:09:22.430
But it's got to be consistent.

01:09:22.430 --> 01:09:22.444
[?

01:09:22.444 --> 01:09:22.529
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: We've got ?]

01:09:22.529 --> 01:09:22.750
[? a-- ?]

01:09:22.750 --> 01:09:23.700
[? Tom. ?]

