01:09:46.890 --> 01:09:48.290
dollar's worthless?

01:09:48.290 --> 01:09:50.399
Do the attorneys decide that
the [INAUDIBLE] going to

01:09:50.399 --> 01:09:51.770
become the world currency?

01:09:51.770 --> 01:09:53.420
Your cash isn't
[? going to work ?] anymore.

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:56.436
It's just inflation drives
the cash of [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:56.436 --> 01:09:57.740
until [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:57.740 --> 01:09:59.110
JOHN DEL VECCHIO: That the
kind of adverse move will

01:09:59.110 --> 01:10:00.040
probably happen fast.

01:10:00.040 --> 01:10:01.440
First of all, it is
going to happen.

01:10:01.440 --> 01:10:03.560
You're going to have
panics and crashes.

01:10:03.560 --> 01:10:05.150
I don't know when it's
going to happen.

01:10:05.150 --> 01:10:07.260
It could be the next year or
the year after, but you're

01:10:07.260 --> 01:10:10.010
getting into an aged bull
market, was kind of my point.

01:10:10.010 --> 01:10:13.160
You're beyond sort of
the normal duration.

01:10:13.160 --> 01:10:15.520
The dollar will probably rally
in that environment, and the

01:10:15.520 --> 01:10:18.750
reason why is that outside of
the United States, there's a

01:10:18.750 --> 01:10:21.890
lot of short dollar trades that
are on by hedge funds,

01:10:21.890 --> 01:10:22.340
for instance.

01:10:22.340 --> 01:10:25.480
They've been using the dollar
as the funding currency for

01:10:25.480 --> 01:10:27.800
their highly levered bets
because the interest rates on

01:10:27.800 --> 01:10:29.030
the dollar are essentially
zero.

01:10:29.030 --> 01:10:31.870
So it's not costing them
much, if anything, to

01:10:31.870 --> 01:10:32.960
put that trade on.

01:10:32.960 --> 01:10:37.040
So when the market tanks, they
have to meet redemptions,

01:10:37.040 --> 01:10:39.090
because people are yanking
money out of their funds.

01:10:39.090 --> 01:10:40.990
When they meet redemptions,
what do they have to do?

01:10:40.990 --> 01:10:42.310
They have to raise cash.

01:10:42.310 --> 01:10:42.960
How do they raise cash?

01:10:42.960 --> 01:10:44.730
They unwind their
short position.

01:10:44.730 --> 01:10:45.850
Where are they most short?

01:10:45.850 --> 01:10:46.740
The dollar.

01:10:46.740 --> 01:10:48.070
So the dollar actually spikes.

01:10:48.070 --> 01:10:50.100
So if you look in 2008,
during a crisis, the

01:10:50.100 --> 01:10:51.500
dollar actually spiked.

01:10:51.500 --> 01:10:53.800
The dollar actually spiked
when the US debt got

01:10:53.800 --> 01:10:55.800
downgraded last year.

01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:56.790
Why?

01:10:56.790 --> 01:11:00.070
Because people got nervous,
and every time they get

01:11:00.070 --> 01:11:01.040
nervous, where do they go?

01:11:01.040 --> 01:11:03.580
They go to the United States
and they repatriated their

01:11:03.580 --> 01:11:04.320
short positions.

01:11:04.320 --> 01:11:05.500
That won't always be the case.

01:11:05.500 --> 01:11:06.660
I think you've got
a valid point

01:11:06.660 --> 01:11:09.490
about the Chinese currency.

01:11:09.490 --> 01:11:11.060
And then, actually, the Chinese
have removed, I

01:11:11.060 --> 01:11:14.210
believe, 10% or 13% of their
treasury holdings this year,

01:11:14.210 --> 01:11:17.220
so they're clearly shifting
away from that.

01:11:17.220 --> 01:11:19.780
So the only reason why the
United States gets away with

01:11:19.780 --> 01:11:22.071
everything that it can do
politically and we can get in

01:11:22.071 --> 01:11:23.790
all this stuff is because
it has the reserve

01:11:23.790 --> 01:11:25.040
currency in the world.

01:11:25.040 --> 01:11:27.290
So as long as that's still the
case, I think you're OK with

01:11:27.290 --> 01:11:27.940
going to cash.

01:11:27.940 --> 01:11:29.755
When that's no longer the
case, then yeah, you

01:11:29.755 --> 01:11:32.390
absolutely need to find
something else.

01:11:32.390 --> 01:11:35.250
But go back to March
of '09 when 45% of

01:11:35.250 --> 01:11:37.560
the AAII was in cash.

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:41.010
Would you have the gumption to
be able to go in there just

01:11:41.010 --> 01:11:42.540
and just buy stock?

01:11:42.540 --> 01:11:43.850
I mean, that's what you
have to ask yourself.

01:11:43.850 --> 01:11:44.950
Only you can answer
that question.

01:11:44.950 --> 01:11:47.550
TOM JACOBS: Well, and here's
how I dealt with it.

01:11:47.550 --> 01:11:51.520
Because I'm valuing stocks all
the time according to cash

01:11:51.520 --> 01:11:57.870
flow, according to net asset
value, after learning in 2000,

01:11:57.870 --> 01:12:00.620
2002, when this started
happening in 2008, and I know

01:12:00.620 --> 01:12:04.160
that small caps get hammered,
but they also bounce back

01:12:04.160 --> 01:12:05.290
faster and higher.

01:12:05.290 --> 01:12:08.820
Because when you sell and you're
liquid, it has more

01:12:08.820 --> 01:12:10.350
effect on the stock price.

01:12:10.350 --> 01:12:11.740
So [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:11.740 --> 01:12:14.840
watching the portfolio go down
and down and down, and what I

01:12:14.840 --> 01:12:18.490
do is I sell the higher valued
stuff, the higher

01:12:18.490 --> 01:12:21.070
ratios, and buy lower.

01:12:21.070 --> 01:12:24.550
And you just keep doing until
there's nothing left that's

01:12:24.550 --> 01:12:26.670
more attractive, and you say,
well, I'm taking losses.

01:12:26.670 --> 01:12:27.590
I'm taking losses.

01:12:27.590 --> 01:12:29.280
Well, it was my rollover IRA.

01:12:29.280 --> 01:12:33.510
But nevertheless, the studies
would show that the returns

01:12:33.510 --> 01:12:37.000
from this outpace the
tax consequences.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:40.400
It got to the point where
it was March 2009.

01:12:40.400 --> 01:12:41.660
I had no idea it
was the bottom.

01:12:41.660 --> 01:12:42.710
Nobody knows.

01:12:42.710 --> 01:12:45.600
John actually has a pretty good
record with market timing

01:12:45.600 --> 01:12:48.210
in certain situations,
but down to the day?

01:12:48.210 --> 01:12:48.570
No.

01:12:48.570 --> 01:12:49.640
Nobody has a clue.

01:12:49.640 --> 01:12:53.200
I, in March 2009, had
nothing more to buy.

01:12:53.200 --> 01:12:57.610
Everything I knew was
a buyout candidate.

01:12:57.610 --> 01:13:00.280
And I just said, OK.

01:13:00.280 --> 01:13:02.660
Some day this is going to
revert to the mean.

01:13:02.660 --> 01:13:08.690
And so I was down a bunch in
2008 and up 70% in 2009.

01:13:08.690 --> 01:13:11.390
But this is the volatility
issue.

01:13:11.390 --> 01:13:13.410
It's why you can make
money in small cap.

01:13:13.410 --> 01:13:15.140
Because people say to
me, well, Tom, I

01:13:15.140 --> 01:13:16.740
didn't have any money.

01:13:16.740 --> 01:13:17.850
Well, you always have money.

01:13:17.850 --> 01:13:21.310
You just have to know what you
own, and then you switch out

01:13:21.310 --> 01:13:24.850
of the less attractive, more
highly valued to the least

01:13:24.850 --> 01:13:27.360
until there's nowhere
more to go.

01:13:27.360 --> 01:13:29.720
Now, if you have the short side,
of course, the short

01:13:29.720 --> 01:13:33.440
side is making you profits
that you can reinvest.

01:13:33.440 --> 01:13:36.920
And so this is a very hard
concept to explain, and also

01:13:36.920 --> 01:13:40.010
it's not something you
can just do in

01:13:40.010 --> 01:13:42.110
10 minutes on Saturday.

01:13:42.110 --> 01:13:43.360
We'll admit that.

